post_cb({"bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_29825655_29825816_0": {"length": 17, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 5884}}, "n3337": {"so_29825655_29825816_0": {"length": 17, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 5655}}, "n4659": {"so_29825655_29825816_0": {"length": 17, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 7367}}}, "29825655": {"ViewCount": "310", "Body": "<p>Given the following class declaration:</p>\n<pre><code>template &lt;int N&gt;\nclass MyClass {\n\npublic:\n    MyClass();\n    ~MyClass();\n};\n</code></pre>\n<p>and the following definitions:</p>\n<pre><code>template &lt;int N&gt; \nMyClass&lt;N&gt;::MyClass() {\n}\n\ntemplate &lt;int N&gt;\nMyClass&lt;N&gt;::~MyClass() {\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>I have two questions:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Do I have to write <code>MyClass::</code> every time (with and without templates)?</li>\n<li>Do I have to write <code>template &lt;int N&gt;</code> before every constructor and destructor?</li>\n</ol>\n", "AcceptedAnswerId": "29825816", "Title": "C++ member function definition class prefix shortcut (also template)", "CreationDate": "2015-04-23T13:55:39.917", "Id": "29825655", "CommentCount": "7", "LastEditDate": "2015-04-23T14:03:21.873", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditorUserId": "2069064", "LastActivityDate": "2015-04-23T14:03:21.873", "Score": "3", "OwnerUserId": "1106899", "Tags": "<c++><class><templates><definition>", "AnswerCount": "1"}, "29825816": {"Id": "29825816", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>From [class.mfct]:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_29825655_29825816_0\">If the definition of a member function is lexically outside its class definition, the member function name shall be qualified by its class name using the :: operator.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>If you are defining your member functions outside of the class definition, you need to write <code>MyClass::</code> every time. Since <code>MyClass</code> is a template, you need to qualify that you're defining the <code>template &lt;int N&gt; MyClass&lt;N&gt;</code> member functions. The answer to both of your questions is yes (although for #2, it's for <em>every</em> member function - not just the constructor and destructor).</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2015-04-23T14:01:57.510", "Score": "2", "CreationDate": "2015-04-23T14:01:57.510", "ParentId": "29825655", "CommentCount": "0", "OwnerUserId": "2069064"}});